    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Shelf Life and Pillow Talk</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By ELAINE LOUIE</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Louie, Elaine</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Samples of fabrics from 1960's, designed by Alexander Girard for Herman Miller Furniture Co, are available as 20-inch-square pillows at Regeneration in SoHo; photo (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>From 1952 to 1973, Alexander Girard designed more than 300 fabrics for the Herman Miller Furniture Company in Zeeland, Mich. Ten of those samples, from the 1960's, are now available as 20-inch-square pillows, right, $75 each at Regeneration in SoHo.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>From 1952 to 1973, Alexander Girard designed more than 300 fabrics for the Herman Miller Furniture Company in Zeeland, Mich. Ten of those samples, from the 1960's, are now available as 20-inch-square pillows, right, $75 each at Regeneration in SoHo.</p>
        <p>The shop also sells a steel and walnut modular shelving system, left, made for ''maximum flexibility,'' said Joseph Fratesi, who designed it with his partner, Thomas Wright. It is 7 1/2 feet high and 24 inches wide, with shelves, lateral files and display racks. The double unit shown is $3,000. Regeneration, 38 Renwick Street (Spring Street); (212) 741-2102.</p>
        <p>ELAINE LOUIE</p>
        <p>CURRENTS: HOME DESIGN</p>
      </block>
